  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering, which involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate, is widely recognized as a criminal activity. \n\nNearly all countries have established legal frameworks to combat money laundering, often in alignment with international standards set by organizations such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, the **United Nations (UN)**, and the **International Monetary Fund (IMF)**. These frameworks typically include regulations that require financial institutions and other entities to report suspicious transactions, conduct due diligence on clients, and maintain records to prevent and detect money laundering activities.\n\nIn addition to national laws, money laundering is also addressed in international treaties and agreements. For example, the **UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (the Palermo Convention)** and the **UN Convention against Corruption (UNCAC)** both include provisions to combat money laundering.\n\nWhile the specific legal definitions and penalties for money laundering may vary by jurisdiction, it is universally condemned as a criminal act that undermines financial systems, facilitates other crimes, and threatens economic stability.",
